{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01G9PnUB3pcbjkYReA154eGA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`elasticsearch-node` is available. The `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` command will fix the voting configuration to allow this single node to form its own cluster.\n\nBut wait - I need to STOP the ES process first before running `unsafe-bootstrap`, then restart it. The unsafe-bootstrap can't be run while ES is running.\n\nActually, let me re-read the docs more carefully. In ES 7.x:\n- `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` - Forces the node to form a new single-node cluster, treating the current cluster state as authoritative. This is for when the cluster has lost too many master nodes.\nSo the challenge in Kubernetes is that I can't directly stop and start the process - I'd need to delete the pod to trigger a restart, but I also need to run unsafe-bootstrap before ES starts back up. An init container or a separate pod running the command against the data directory might work. Though actually, the pod is already running with a failing readiness probe, so the cluster can't elect a master. The unsafe-bootstrap command requires the node to be stopped first.\n\nI'm thinking through the mechanics: if I scale the StatefulSet down to zero replicas, that stops the pod cleanly, then I could potentially run the unsafe-bootstrap command against the persistent volume before scaling back up.\n\nBut I need to verify whether unsafe-bootstrap actually requires the node to be completely shut down or if there's any way to run it while Elasticsearch is still active. Looking at the documentation, it's clear that the tool needs exclusive access to modify the cluster state on disk, so the node must be stopped first. In Elasticsearch 7.x with Zen2, a node reads its stored cluster state on boot and looks for other nodes in discovery.seed_hosts to form quorum. Since the voting configuration was originally {es-cluster-0, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-2}, you'd need at least 2 votes to elect a master, but with only es-cluster-0 available, quorum can't be reached. The `unsafe-bootstrap` command resets the voting configuration to just {es-cluster-0}, allowing it to reach quorum and form a cluster on its own.\n\nI'm also considering whether voting exclusions might be stored separately and preventing es-cluster-0 from voting even if the stored configuration still lists all three nodes—if exclusions were added but the cluster state wasn't committed before the nodes died, that could be the issue. But modifying the stored data directly would require understanding Elasticsearch's Lucene codec, which is risky. The safest path forward is using `unsafe-bootstrap`.\n\nMy plan is to scale the StatefulSet down to zero, spin up a debug pod with the Elasticsearch image that mounts the PVC, run the unsafe-bootstrap command, then scale back up and monitor the recovery. I'm weighing the safest approach here. Scaling the StatefulSet to zero, then using a debug pod with the same image and PVC mount to run the unsafe-bootstrap command as the elasticsearch user, then scaling back up seems like the cleanest option to avoid race conditions. Let me find the PVC name first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":637,"cache_read_input_tokens":43942,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":637},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0d02f213-de47-4af6-8a02-e35203f323ec","uuid":"89ed7b90-4edc-409d-97d4-3c9d5204bbbf","request_id":"req_011CbyB8SxGgQ9TqQP9Ghpxq"}
